TDD exercise complete. Here's a summary:

**9/9 tests passing** - Conway's Game of Life implemented via strict TDD Red-Green-Refactor cycle.

**TDD Cycle Summary:**

| Test | Red | Green | Refactor |
|------|-----|-------|----------|
| 1. Empty grid → empty | Fail (undefined) | return [] | No-op (minimal) |
| 2. Single cell dies | Pass immediately | Skip | Skip |
| 3. Two adjacent cells die | Pass immediately | Skip | Skip |
| 4. Cell with 2 neighbors survives | Fail (missing cell) | Filter by count===2 | Extracted neighborOffsets array |
| 5. Cell with 3 neighbors survives | Fail (count===2 only) | count===2 \|\| count===3 | Extracted NEIGHBOR_OFFSETS constant |
| 6. Cell with 4 neighbors dies | Pass immediately | Skip | Skip |
| 7. Dead cell reproduction | Fail (no birth logic) | Added dead candidate scanning + birth | Introduced Set for O(1) lookups |
| 8. Block (still life) | Pass immediately | Skip | Skip |
| 9. Blinker (oscillator) | Pass immediately | Skip | Skip |

**Key implementation decisions driven by tests:**
- Tests 1-3 drove the hardcoded `return []` (all death cases)
- Test 4 forced neighbor counting logic
- Test 5 widened survival to include 3 neighbors
- Test 7 was the pivotal test requiring reproduction (dead cell birth) logic
